"reviewcomment":"This place as ruined me<br><br>I think I met the French equivalent of the Soup Nazi.  The owner and staff do not speak english.  Perhaps they speak &#34;no photos&#34; and that&#39;s about it.  I had a feeling that they speak more than that but I think I found the proverbial &#34;rude french&#34; service I had heard about.  For example, when I ask &#34;what is in this?&#34;  I would be met with some french speak and I am certain it was not a real explanation of what was in it.  No smiles, no pointing I am certain they know the terms &#34;apple&#34; or &#34;currant.&#34;  Still we got nothing in terms of explanation. . .<br><br>This place is not really near any touristy areas.  I had to walk many blocks just to get here. <br><br>Having said that, this place is AMAZING.  After the first day, we had to walk back on an other day in the middle of a thunderstorm so that we could buy their pastries.  The whole time in the rain, my main goal was to protect the damn breads we bought.  <br><br>Really, everything here is ridiculously good.  I am forever ruined.  Just the other day, I took a bite of a Costco croissant and had to wipe a tear.  I will never eat pastries again without knowing how much better it is supposed to be. . .<br><br>try their apple or currant turnovers.  get the pastrie that looks like a caramel apple.  If you don&#39;t go here to eat a chocolate croissant, you have seriously missed out on a true gem.  People talk about how this is &#34;pricey&#34; I would have gladly paid double what they charge.  They obviously care about what they do and they should be paid accordingly.",
