"reviewcomment":"La Bague de Kenza seems to be a fusion between Middle Eastern and French baked goods, which is a fabulous idea. This can be seen in their vast mountains of goodies that don&#39;t appear to be too French, but with a hint of ingredients that are commonly used in Turkey, Lebanon, and other nations.<br><br>The first thing I tried is a pastry with formage. It was perfectly flaky, very tasty on the inside with a sweet cheese flavor, almost like the sweet cheese flavor on Russian danishes. We also had something that resembles the famous Turkish kanafeh, a vermicelli-like pastry. Not too sweet and a great texture overall. <br><br>The employees here are very friendly. Even if their English is limited, they try their best to explain everything with a smile on their face. They have a policy where eating in the bakery costs more, which we didn&#39;t know at first. My dad sat down with our to go bags, and only then did we remember this policy that is quite common in France. The ladies were completely fine with it, and even took our goodies and plated them for us free of charge. We couldn&#39;t just leave without a tip for such thoughtful service.",
