"rating":"3.5",
"reviewcomment":"3.25 stars<br>Bonus points: diaper changing area, stroller parking<br><br>A tiny, but cute, makes you say &#34;awwwww&#34; kind of parent-children café and activity space. You know, one of those places that uses the Curlz font on all of their publicity. Upstairs is the café, which has drinks and small nibbles. They&#39;ve got stroller parking in the back (hard to navigate to with all the tables, though) and even a changing room. Downstairs is the space for the ateliers. They host numerous different events for both children and parents to be. The activities aren&#39;t cheap, but not as expensive as some of the other kids events in Paris. My biggest issue with Le Poussette is that they only have 1 type of beer on the menu. That&#39;s it. No.other.alcohol. I&#39;m not sure how other people mentally manage toddlers. Me, I need a bit more than tea and cake. But, at least I could put my kid down in the very small (probably 6m2) play area in the café and look on while other people&#39;s children entertain mine for a while. They have a wall full of unnecessary and over-priced children items for sale in the café as well. And, all of these things are within arms reach of the children. Wise plan for increasing their sales. I think when most of the kids grab stuff, their parents feel obligated to buy it. When my kid started pulling things down (and, shhhh, don&#39;t tell anyone - pulled the head off a doll that I secretly replaced and put back on the shelf), I glance at the staff with a &#34;you know, this is your fault&#34; look on my face and they feel responsible. I&#39;m picking up on the French technique of never taking the blame for anything that goes wrong. It&#39;s a nice stop if you&#39;re in the area and need to do a fast diaper change or a break during a day out with the stroller.",
