"ogimage":"http://s3-media1.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/msSwV-7U-Q-j8LmkNupSsQ/l.jpg",
"rating":"4.0",
"reviewcomment":"I don&#39;t understand how I can possibly be the first to review this quirky little café! My sweetheart and I popped in one afternoon during our recent holiday in Paris - just walking down the street, taking it all in, when the name caught my eye - I&#39;ve always associated the word &#34;crepuscular&#34; with something foreboding and Lovecraftian! A hankering for crêpes ensued, and so.<br><br>The interior is very lo-fi, a little odd, a little artsy, with posters for plays and so on - the sort of thing I&#39;m used to in hole-in-the-walls in Oakland and Berkeley but didn&#39;t necessarily expect to see in Paris, so it was a little funnily familiar. The windows afford a nice view of the street, perfect for people watching on a mellow afternoon.<br><br>The proprietor and chef was so, so nice! I love that he asked us if we wanted &#34;salt or sweet.&#34; I got the vegetarian crêpe (salt), and I cannot express how happy I am that it was prepared on the spot,* crêpe, veggies and all. It was perfectly crisped on the exterior, wonderfully savory and generously portioned. <br><br>My omnivorous sweetheart ordered an andouille crêpe (also salt), and was warned it was &#34;very traditional.&#34; I&#39;m not entirely sure what that meant, but while I will never call my sweetheart unadventurous I have perhaps never been so glad to be a vegetarian. <br><br>We split a dessert crêpe (sweet) afterwards, and it was amazing.<br><br>To sum up: there was nothing foreboding about it! The service was kind and honest, the food was delicious, and it was an enjoyable time. And now I&#39;ve eaten crêpes in Paris!<br><br>*Is the proper phrase &#34;a la minute?&#34;**<br><br>** It is &#34;fraîchement préparé!&#34; Merci, Elodie!",
