"ogimage":"http://s3-media4.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/gOat6g8peFuiScDYu0JuvQ/l.jpg",
"rating":"5.0",
"reviewcomment":"There are a lot of famous chocolate houses in Paris (Patrick Roger, Maison du Chocolate, Pierre Marcolini...to name a few) but Fouquet is one of the oldest (est. 1853). It is also one of the best. <br><br>Bizarrely very few people know about it, making it one of the most delicious, unknown master brands in Paris. I had first heard about it through David Lebovitz&#39;s blog after he wrote glowingly about a tasting tour he had taken of the brand&#39;s Parisian laboratory where everything from peanut shelling, chocolates and candies are done by hand using artisanal techniques passed along from one generation to the other. <br><br>I noticed a year later that the brand had opened a swanky new shop with an updated look near the Marche St Honoré and was excited when I was invited for a private tasting/visit to really get to know the brand. The owner was on hand to talk about the history of the brand, explain how the chocolates and candies were fabricated, and let us taste some of the key products in the collection, all presented in gorgeous boxes, tins and glass jars.<br><br>Everything was OUT OF THIS WORLD! From the molten marshmallows and chocolate-covered roasted almonds, to the prailines, mendiants and pate de fruit I have never tasted such an all-around phenomenal range of sweets. <br><br>How this place remains a secret is beyond me!",
