"categorystrlist":"Fast Food & Takeaways,     Coffee & Tea,     Cafes",
"ogimage":"http://s3-media1.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/On0jmKIl9foS2LoI4AJq4Q/l.jpg",
"rating":"3.5",
"reviewcomment":"Ok, ok, you think it&#39;s declassee to visit  Starbucks in Paris (or anywhere outside of the US) but I don&#39;t   There is a lot to be learned from hanging<br>with the natives whether you&#39;re at Montparnasse or in Bejiing, CHina<br>as i was a few years ago, and where the sound of someone repeating<br>my order for a no foam latte, with a french or Chinese accent is a  worthy cultural experience.  The lattes actually taste pretty similar although in Paris, the milk they use is not quite the same .  NO matter-you go to<br>see who is hanging out, use the facilities and stand back in amazement<br>at the crowds!!  From NYC to Paris to Bangkok, Starbucks is apparently<br>the place to see and be eeen.  This is the ONLY Stbux i visit in Paris, for a variety of reasons-I once wanted a tee shirt, which they di d not have and the French male barristo gave me the one off of his back!!  It is<br>still enshrined in a place of honor in my home.  Stbuks is as expensive in <br>Paris as anywhere-and with this visit in Jan 2012 I was amazed to see<br>the number of competitive internet cafes which have sprung up  in<br>the area.  I did sample a few, the coffee is good, the internet connection<br>is fast but if you want Starbucks coffee and the flavor of all that<br>the brand conveys, then there is nothing like the one at Montparnasse.",
